      <![CDATA[<h1 id="Grub-Rescue-Unknown-Filesystem-but-you-can"><a href="#Grub-Rescue-Unknown-Filesystem-but-you-can" class="headerlink" title="Grub Rescue Unknown Filesystem, but you can!"></a>Grub Rescue Unknown Filesystem, but you can!</h1><blockquote><p>If you are working with computers especially dual-system, you may have gotten such situation showed below. It means the computer can’t find the correct <a href="https://zh.wikipedia.org/wiki/GNU_GRUB">Grub, Grand Unified Bootloader.</a> So you need to help him load the correct file.</p></blockquote><hr><p>If you want to solve it, follow the steps and you can make it.</p><span id="more"></span><h2 id="Steps"><a href="#Steps" class="headerlink" title="Steps"></a>Steps</h2><ol><li><p>Pre-condition.<br>Just make sure your grub <strong>works</strong> fine</p></li><li><p>Type ls to get all available things.</p><figure class="highlight plaintext"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">grub rescue &gt; ls</span><br><span class="line">(hd0) (hd0,msdos1) (hd0,msdos3) .... (hd1,msdos8)</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure></li><li><p>Type ls every_result, such as ls (hd0,msdos1), got before. And remember the result(s) whose output is different from others.</p><figure class="highlight plaintext"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">grub rescue &gt; ls (hd0)</span><br><span class="line">grub rescue &gt; ls (hd0,msdos1)</span><br><span class="line">...</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure></li><li><p>Type <strong>ls</strong> special_result&#x2F;boot&#x2F;grub to find whether there is grub or not.</p><figure class="highlight plaintext"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">grub rescue &gt; ls (hd0,msdos1)/boot/grub</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure></li><li><p>If it is, then congratulations to you. You have find the correct grub. And now, all you need to do is <strong>reset</strong> it.</p><figure class="highlight plaintext"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br><span class="line">2</span><br><span class="line">3</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">grub rescue &gt; set root=(hd0,msdos1)</span><br><span class="line">grub rescue &gt; set prefix=(hd0,msdos1)/boot/grub</span><br><span class="line">grub rescue &gt; insmod /boot/grub/normal.mod</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure></li><li><p>After step 5, the “grub rescue &gt;” will be brighter.</p><figure class="highlight plaintext"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><span class="line">grub rescue &gt; normal</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure></li></ol><hr><h2 id="Congratulations"><a href="#Congratulations" class="headerlink" title="Congratulations!"></a>Congratulations!</h2><p>Your computer can start normally. And enjoy it :)</p><p>11th Nov 2015</p>]]>
    </content>
